  const result = a + b
  return result
}

4. â— No own this, arguments, or super
Arrow functions do not bind their own this.
They inherit this from the outer scope.

ğŸ§  Arrow Functions and this
ğŸ”¥ Arrow functions do NOT have their own this.
They inherit this from the surrounding (lexical) scope.

âœ… Quick Recap of Key Differences
| Feature            | Regular Function            | Arrow Function (`=>`)         |
| ------------------ | --------------------------- | ----------------------------- |
| `this` binding     | Dynamic (depends on caller) | Lexical (inherits from outer) |
| `arguments` object | Available                   | Not available                 |
| Short syntax       | âŒ                           | âœ…                             |
| Method definitions | âœ… Recommended               | âŒ Avoid (for methods)         |

âœ… Syntax Rules
| Rule                              | Description     | Example                      |
| --------------------------------- | --------------- | ---------------------------- |
| No parentheses for one param      | Allowed         | `x => x * 2`                 |
| Parentheses for 0 or 2+ params    | Required        | `(a, b) => a + b`            |
| No `return` needed for one-liners | Implicit return | `x => x + 1`                 |
| Braces require `return`           | If using `{}`   | `(x, y) => { return x + y }` |

âš ï¸ When to Avoid Arrow Functions
âŒ As methods in objects

âŒ As constructors (they canâ€™t be used with new)

âŒ When this, arguments, or super are needed

âœ… Use Cases for Arrow Functions
âœ… Short utility functions

âœ… Callbacks (e.g. map, filter, forEach)

âœ… Inside other functions (inherit this)

âœ… When you donâ€™t need your own this

